               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-353-person2562">
                  DANIEL 
                  SARGENT
               <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2562" type="surname" value="SARGENT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2562" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a waiter at <placeName id="t18270913-353-crimeloc1963">Baker's coffee-house, Cornhill</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-353-crimeloc1963" type="placeName" value="Baker's coffee-house, Cornhill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-353-crimeloc1963" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-353-off1961 t18270913-353-crimeloc1963"></join>, which is kept by William Gibson. On Friday, the 17th of August, the prisoner came there about half-past one o'clock; he went up stairs into the coffee-room; I asked if he was going to dine; he said No, he was going to wait a little time; he asked for a paper, but there was none; he asked for a glass of sherry, which I went down and got him; I thought he was looking at the tables, and before I went for it I counted the spoons - one table had four on it, another three, and another two; when I returned with the sherry I counted them again, and they were right; I went down and told Mr. Gibson; I went up again, and then one of them was gone - the prisoner was then coming out of the room; I said, "I must detain you;" he said, "For what?" I said, "For a spoon;" and he produced it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CRESWELL. Q. What part of his person did he take it from? A. I could not see, as he turned round; he gave Mr. Gibson his name and address when he came up.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-353-person2563">
                  JOHN 
                  COLLING
               <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2563" type="surname" value="COLLING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2563" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2563" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was dining at this coffee-house; Sargent went down; he came up again, and accused the prisoner, who seemed in great trepidation, and took up the newspaper, and, after perusing it for a moment, he was endeavouring to take something from his pocket, and then on a table, on which I had seen but three spoons, I saw four; one was a different sort to the others; I will not swear he placed it there.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-353-person2564">
                  JOHN 
                  DIXON SMITH
               <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2564" type="surname" value="DIXON SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2564" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-person2564" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I went to the coffee-house, and took the prisoner; he was accused of taking one spoon from the George and Vulture, and one from Mr. Gibson.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I put it to the Jury to say whether I could commit the offence, as I am not in want of character, money, or business.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received an excellent character</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18270913-353-verdict1964" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18270913-353-verdict1964" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 30.</p>
